result.execSummary:
The defendant Tracey J Loucks was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Issue of Worthless Checks(<=$2500), a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.24(1).
  • Issue of Worthless Checks(<=$2500), a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.24(1).
  • Issue of Worthless Checks(<=$2500), a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.24(1).
  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

09:30 AM Defendant Tracey J Loucks in court.  Probation agent Patricia Grabow appears in court. 
Court is not aware if the state intended to appear today.   

Defendant is sworn by the clerk. 
Court questions the defendant.  
Defendant updates her address and is living with a friend.  She just got out of a serious domestic violence situation.  There are charges for Disorderly Conduct-Domestic Abuse that are currently pending for the abuser.  She had been working at Grazie's and Hampton Inn.  She was off of work most of last year because she had medical issues.   Her hours varied between 10 to 30 hours.  After her medical issues she was then only at Hampton Inn working full-time.  She has graduated high school and received an associates degree.  She worked 3 years at a domestic shelter and worked in the medical field.  Being on probation has prohibited her from obtaining jobs.  She has a current job opening at Associated Bank but only if she's off probation.  Then also at Starbucks.  She has paperwork from Associated Bank confirming that information.  She would be working as a Customer Care Representative.  Aerotech company is the one who reached out to her because of her work history but her criminal history is an issue.  Depending on today, she could possibly start on Monday May 13th. 
Court reviews the letter submitted by the defendant.  This letter does not provide the information for Associated Bank. 
Defendant indicates because all of her mail is general delivery, she has not received the letter that confirms that she won't be hired if she is on probation. 
Court questions why she has paid so little on her restitution. 
Defendant indicates she did not receive short term disability while she had her medical issues.  
Court questions her further regarding the medical issues. 
Defendant indicates she is 100% recovered.  
Court questions if she has other employment opportunities.
Defendant indicates she starts at Starbucks on Thursday.  They have medical, vision and dental insurance and will pay for her to be continuing her education to finish her bachelors degree in Human Services. 
Court questions Atty Grabow. 
Atty Grabow makes statements.  She has only supervised her since December.  There are no violations and she is on minimum so she only comes in once every 3 months.  
Court indicates restitution is the big issue. 

BY THE COURT: 
Court extends the defendant's probation for a period of 18 months unless she provides proof to the probation department by May 3, 2019 that she cannot be on probation and get the job at Associated Bank.  If she provides proof, probation will be allowed to terminate and civil judgments will be entered.   She did testify under oath and she could be subject to purgery.  If she cannot prove that, she is expected to make gains in the payment of restitution during the extended period.
